{
  "text": "In previous studies, we found annular dilation and leaflet lengthening of the mitral valve in response to elevated mechanical load in the adult heart [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These morphological changes in valve structure have important consequences. In a sheep model of chronic ischemic mitral regurgitation, annular dilation and leaflet lengthening increased anterior and posterior leaflet radii of curvature [CITATION_4] . Why might this be important? The mitral annulus, leaflets, and chordal apparatus bear the load generated by the pressure in the left ventricle. Leaflet stress is known to be a stimulus that is likely to drive valve remodeling, due to the LaPlace relationship ( Values are expressed as means \u03ee SE. P1-P3, posterior leaflet scallops 1-3. For both groups, n \u03ed 5. *P \u03fd 0.05 by unpaired t-test. such changes on a curved surface: S w \u03ed (P t /2) \u03eb (r/h), where S w is leaflet wall stress, P t is transmural pressure, r is radius of curvature, and h is wall thickness.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "15996074",
    "[CITATION_2]": "9947703",
